{{Expand Arabic|مولود قاسم نايت بلقاسم|date=February 2017}}
'''Mouloud Kacem Naît Belkacem''' (6 January 1927 in Belaâyane, [[Ighil Ali]] - 27 August 1992)  was an Algerian politician, philosopher, historian, and writer. He was a noted defender of the Arabic language, Islam and Algerian nationalism, and stressed the importance of Arabic identity in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djazairess.com/fr/apsfr/95716|title="La problématique identitaire chez Mouloud Kacem Naït Belkacem et la mondialisation", thème d'un séminaire à Batna |publisher=Djazairess.com|accessdate=3 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>

He studied in Tunis and Cairo, where he obtained a degree in philosophy. He then attended [[Sorbonne]], and was a member of the Arabic academies in Jordan, Egypt and Syria, before he joined the [[Algerian revolution]] in 1954.<ref name="const">{{cite web|url=http://www.constantine-aps.dz/spip.php?page=imprimer&id_article=14919|title=LA CONTRIBUTION INTELLECTUELLE DE MOULOUD KACEM NAIT BELKACEM|publisher=Constantine-aps.dz|accessdate=3 May 2015|language=French}}</ref> In the 1970s he held various government posts, including Minister of Habous in 1970, Minister of Religious Affairs and Endowments from 1970 to 1977, and Minister to the President of the Republic, in charge of religious affairs from 1977 to 1979.<ref name="const"/> He was also in charge of High Council of the Arabic language.

